<IMG SRC="g15347g12_97.jpg" ALT="LOGO"> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B>APPLE INC. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>NOTICE OF ANNUAL MEETING OF SHAREHOLDERS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>To Be Held On March&nbsp;4, 2008 </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To Holders of Common Stock of Apple Inc.: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Notice is hereby
given that the Annual Meeting of Shareholders of Apple Inc., a California corporation (the &#147;<I>Company</I>&#148;), will be held on Tuesday, March&nbsp;4, 2008 at 10:00&nbsp;a.m. local time, at the Company&#146;s principal executive offices
located at 1 Infinite Loop, Building 4, Cupertino, California 95014, for the following purposes, as more fully described in the accompanying Proxy Statement: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">1.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To elect the Company&#146;s Board of Directors. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To ratify the appointment of KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm for fiscal year 2008. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To consider two shareholder proposals, if properly presented at the meeting. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">4.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To transact such other business as may properly come before the meeting and any postponement(s)&nbsp;or adjournment(s)&nbsp;thereof. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">All shareholders are cordially invited to attend the meeting in person. However, to ensure that each shareholder&#146;s vote is counted at the meeting,
shareholders are requested to mark, sign, date and return the enclosed proxy card as promptly as possible in the envelope provided or to submit the proxy via the Internet or by telephone. Shareholders attending the meeting may vote in person even if
they have previously returned proxy cards. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Only shareholders of record as of the close of business on January&nbsp;15, 2008 are entitled
to receive notice of, to attend and to vote at the meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV ALIGN="right">

<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>General Counsel and Secretary</I></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Cupertino, California </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman"
SIZE="2">January&nbsp;22, 2008 </FONT></P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center">

<IMG SRC="g15347g12_97.jpg" ALT="LOGO"> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="4"><B>APPLE INC. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>1 Infinite Loop </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Cupertino, California 95014 </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>PROXY STATEMENT </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Introduction </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The enclosed proxy is solicited on behalf of the Board of Directors (the &#147;<I>Board</I>&#148;) of Apple Inc., a California corporation (the
&#147;<I>Company</I>&#148;), for use at the Company&#146;s annual meeting of shareholders (the&nbsp;&#147;<I>Annual Meeting</I>&#148;) to be held on Tuesday, March&nbsp;4, 2008 at 10:00&nbsp;a.m. local time, and at any postponement(s)&nbsp;or
adjournment(s)&nbsp;thereof. The purposes of the Annual Meeting are set forth in this proxy statement (this&nbsp;&#147;<I>Proxy Statement</I>&#148;) and in the accompanying Notice of Annual Meeting of Shareholders. The Annual Meeting will be held at
the Company&#146;s principal executive offices in Building 4 at the address shown above. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s complete mailing address is 1
Infinite Loop, Cupertino, California&nbsp;95014, and its telephone number is (408)&nbsp;996-1010. Georgeson Inc., which is assisting with the mechanics of the return of the proxies, may be contacted at (800)&nbsp;261-1052. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">These proxy solicitation materials were first sent on or about January&nbsp;22, 2008 to all shareholders entitled to vote at the Annual Meeting.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Procedural Matters </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Only shareholders
of record as of the close of business on January&nbsp;15, 2008 (the &#147;<I>Record Date</I>&#148;) are entitled to receive notice of, to attend, and to vote at the Annual Meeting. There were 878,795,201 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock
issued and outstanding on the Record Date, held by 31,035 holders of record. Each share has one vote on each matter. The closing sale price of the Company&#146;s common stock as reported on the NASDAQ Global Select Market on the Record Date was
$169.04 per share. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">A shareholder may revoke any proxy given pursuant to this solicitation by attending the Annual Meeting and voting in
person, or by delivering to the Company&#146;s Corporate Secretary at the Company&#146;s principal executive offices referred to above, prior to the Annual Meeting, a written notice of revocation or a duly executed proxy bearing a date later than
that of the previously submitted proxy. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company will bear the cost of this solicitation. The Company has retained the services of
Georgeson&nbsp;Inc. to assist in obtaining proxies from brokers and nominees of shareholders for the Annual Meeting. The estimated cost of such services is $14,000 plus out-of-pocket expenses. In addition, the Company will reimburse brokerage firms
and other persons representing beneficial owners of shares for their reasonable expenses in forwarding solicitation material to such beneficial owners. Certain of the Company&#146;s directors, officers and regular employees, without additional
compensation, may solicit proxies personally or by telephone, facsimile or email. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Attendance at the Annual Meeting is limited to
shareholders. Admission to the Annual Meeting will be on a first-come, first-served basis. Registration will begin at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. local time and each shareholder may be asked to present valid picture identification such as a driver&#146;s license
or passport. The use of cell phones, PDAs, pagers, recording and photographic equipment, camera phones and/or computers is not permitted in the meeting rooms at the Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">1 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Voting of Proxies </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">All valid proxies received prior to the Annual Meeting will be voted. All shares represented by a proxy will be voted, and where a shareholder specifies by means of the proxy a choice with respect to any matter to be
acted upon, the shares will be voted in accordance with the specification so made. If no choice is indicated on the proxy, the shares will be voted FOR each of the nominees of the Board (Proposal No.&nbsp;1), FOR the ratification of the appointment
of KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm for fiscal year 2008 (Proposal No.&nbsp;2), AGAINST each shareholder proposal, if properly presented at the Annual Meeting (Proposals No.&nbsp;3 and No.&nbsp;4) and as
the proxy holders may determine in their discretion with respect to any other matters that properly come before the Annual Meeting. See &#147;<B>OTHER MATTERS</B>.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Quorum </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For business to be conducted at the Annual Meeting, a quorum must be present. The presence at
the Annual Meeting, either in person or by proxy, of holders of shares of outstanding common stock entitled to vote and representing a majority of the voting power of such shares will constitute a quorum for the transaction of business. Abstentions
and &#147;broker non-votes&#148; (i.e., shares held by a broker or nominee that are represented at the Annual Meeting, but with respect to which such broker or nominee is not instructed to vote on a particular proposal and does not have
discretionary voting power) will be counted for the purpose of determining whether a quorum is present for the transaction of business. If a quorum is not present, the Annual Meeting will be adjourned until a quorum is obtained. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Votes Required; Abstentions; Broker Non-Votes </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For
Proposal No.&nbsp;1, the eight nominees receiving the highest number of affirmative votes of the outstanding shares of the Company&#146;s common stock present or represented by proxy and voting at the Annual Meeting will be elected as directors to
serve until the next annual meeting of shareholders and until their successors are duly elected and qualified. Abstentions will have no effect on the outcome of the election of candidates for director. Additionally, the election of directors is a
matter on which a broker or other nominee is generally empowered to vote, and therefore no broker non-votes are expected to exist in connection with Proposal No.&nbsp;1. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Approval of Proposals No.&nbsp;2, No.&nbsp;3 and No.&nbsp;4 require a vote that satisfies two criteria: (i)&nbsp;the affirmative vote must constitute a majority of the voting power present or represented by proxy and
voting at the Annual Meeting and (ii)&nbsp;the affirmative vote must constitute a majority of the voting power required to constitute the quorum. For purposes of these proposals, abstentions and broker non-votes will not affect the outcome under
clause (i), which recognizes only actual votes cast for or against the proposal. However, abstentions and broker non-votes may affect the outcome under clause (ii)&nbsp;because abstentions and broker non-votes are counted for purposes of determining
the quorum and have the effect of a vote against the proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The ratification of the appointment of the independent registered public
accounting firm for the 2008 fiscal year is a matter on which a broker or other nominee is generally empowered to vote. Accordingly, no broker non-votes are expected to exist in connection with Proposal No.&nbsp;2. In contrast, since shareholder
proposals are not matters on which brokers are empowered to vote without instructions, there may be broker non-votes on Proposals No.&nbsp;3 and No. 4. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman"
SIZE="2"><B>Voting via the Internet and by Telephone </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Shareholders whose shares are registered in the name of a bank or brokerage firm
may be eligible to vote electronically through the Internet or by telephone. Many banks and brokerage firms participate in the Broadridge Financial Solutions, Inc. (&#147;<I>Broadridge</I>&#148;) online and telephone program. This program provides
eligible shareholders the opportunity to vote via the Internet or by telephone. Voting forms will provide instructions for shareholders whose banks or brokerage firms participate in Broadridge&#146;s online and telephone program. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Registered shareholders may vote electronically through the Internet or by telephone by following the
instructions included with their proxy card. A shareholder not wishing to vote electronically through the Internet or by telephone or whose form does not reference Internet or telephone voting information should complete and return the enclosed
paper proxy card. Signing and returning the proxy card or submitting the proxy via the Internet or by telephone does not affect the right to vote in person at the Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Internet and Electronic Availability of Proxy Materials </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As permitted by the Securities and Exchange
Commission (the &#147;<I>SEC</I>&#148;), the Company is sending a Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials (the &#147;<I>Notice</I>&#148;) to shareholders who hold shares in &#147;street name&#148; through a bank, broker or other holder of
record. All such shareholders will have the ability to access this Proxy Statement and the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the fiscal year ended September&nbsp;29, 2007 as filed with the SEC on November&nbsp;15, 2007 (the
&#147;<I>Annual Report</I>&#148;) on a website referred to in the Notice or to request a printed set of these materials at no charge. Instructions on how to access these materials over the Internet or to request a printed copy may be found in the
Notice. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, any shareholder may request to receive proxy materials in printed form by mail or electronically by email on an
ongoing basis. Choosing to receive future proxy materials by email will save the Company the cost of printing and mailing documents to shareholders and will reduce the impact of annual meetings on the environment. A shareholder&#146;s election to
receive proxy materials by email will remain in effect until the shareholder terminates it. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Directors </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Listed below are the Company&#146;s eight directors. The Board appointed Ms.&nbsp;Andrea Jung to fill a vacancy on the Board on January&nbsp;4, 2008 and
has nominated her for election at the Annual Meeting. The remaining seven of the Company&#146;s directors are nominated for re-election at the Annual Meeting. All of the directors elected at the Annual Meeting will serve a one-year term expiring at
the next annual meeting of shareholders. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>William&nbsp;V. Campbell</B> has been the Chairman of the Board of Directors of
Intuit,&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;<I>Intuit</I>&#148;) since August&nbsp;1998. From September&nbsp;1999 to January&nbsp;2000, Mr.&nbsp;Campbell acted as the Chief Executive Officer of Intuit. From January&nbsp;1994 to August&nbsp;1998, Mr.&nbsp;Campbell was
the President and Chief Executive Officer and a director of Intuit. From January&nbsp;1991 to December&nbsp;1993, Mr.&nbsp;Campbell was the President and Chief Executive Officer of GO Corporation. Mr. Campbell is also a member of the Board of
Directors of Highlands Acquisition Corp., a blank check company formed for the purpose of acquiring one or more operating businesses. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman"
SIZE="2"><B>Millard S. Drexler</B> has been the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of J.&nbsp;Crew Group,&nbsp;Inc. since January&nbsp;2003. Previously, Mr.&nbsp;Drexler was the Chief Executive Officer of Gap&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;<I>Gap</I>&#148;)
from 1995 and President from 1987 until September 2002. Mr.&nbsp;Drexler was also a member of the Board of Directors of Gap from November&nbsp;1983 until October&nbsp;2002. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">3 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Albert A. Gore,&nbsp;Jr.</B> has served as a Senior Advisor to Google,&nbsp;Inc.
(&#147;<I>Google</I>&#148;) since 2001. He has also served as the Executive Chairman of Current&nbsp;TV since 2002, the Chairman of Generation Investment Management since 2004 and a partner of Kleiner Perkins Caufield&nbsp;&amp; Byers since 2007. He
is a visiting professor at Middle Tennessee State University. Mr.&nbsp;Gore was inaugurated as the 45th Vice President of the United States in 1993. He was re-elected in 1996 and served for a total of eight years as President of the Senate, a member
of the Cabinet and the National Security Council. Prior to 1993, he served eight years in the U.S. Senate and eight years in the U.S. House of Representatives. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Steven P. Jobs</B> is one of the Company&#146;s co-founders and currently serves as its Chief Executive Officer (the &#147;<I>CEO</I>&#148;). Mr.&nbsp;Jobs is also a director of The Walt Disney Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Andrea Jung </B>has been Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Avon Products, Inc. (&#147;<I>Avon</I>&#148;) since September 2001, having
previously served as Chief Executive Officer of Avon since November 1999. Ms.&nbsp;Jung has been a member of the Board of Directors of Avon since January 1998 and was President from January 1998 to January 2001 and Chief Operating Officer from July
1998 to November 1999. She was elected Executive Vice President of Avon in March 1997 concurrently continuing as President, Global Marketing, a position she held from July 1996 to the end of 1997. Ms.&nbsp;Jung joined Avon in January 1994 as
President, Product Marketing for Avon U.S. Previously, she was Executive Vice President for Neiman Marcus and a Senior Vice President for I.&nbsp;Magnin. Ms.&nbsp;Jung is a director of the General Electric Company. She is also a member of the N.Y.
Presbyterian Hospital Board of Trustees and a director of Catalyst, a nonprofit corporate membership research and advisory organization. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman"
SIZE="2"><B>Arthur D. Levinson,&nbsp;Ph.D.</B> has been the Chief Executive Officer and a Director of Genentech&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;<I>Genentech</I>&#148;) since July&nbsp;1995. Dr.&nbsp;Levinson has been the Chairman of the Board of Directors of
Genentech since September&nbsp;1999. He joined Genentech in 1980 and served in a number of executive positions, including the Senior Vice President of Research and Development from 1993 to 1995. Dr.&nbsp;Levinson is also a member of the Board of
Directors of Google. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Eric E. Schmidt,&nbsp;Ph.D.</B> has served as the Chief Executive Officer of Google since July&nbsp;2001 and as a
member of Google&#146;s Board of Directors since March&nbsp;2001, where he served as the Chairman of the Board from March&nbsp;2001 to April&nbsp;2004. In April&nbsp;2004, Dr.&nbsp;Schmidt was named the Chairman of the Executive Committee of
Google&#146;s Board of Directors. From April&nbsp;1997 to November&nbsp;2001, Dr.&nbsp;Schmidt served as Chairman of the Board of Directors of Novell,&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;<I>Novell</I>&#148;), a computer networking company, and, from April&nbsp;1997 to
July&nbsp;2001, as the Chief Executive Officer of Novell. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Jerome B. York</B> has been the Chief Executive Officer of Harwinton Capital
LLC (formerly Harwinton Capital Corporation), a private investment company that he controls, since September&nbsp;2003. From January&nbsp;2000 until September&nbsp;2003, Mr.&nbsp;York was the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of
MicroWarehouse,&nbsp;Inc., a reseller of computer hardware, software and peripheral products. From September&nbsp;1995 to October&nbsp;1999, he was the Vice Chairman of Tracinda Corporation. From May&nbsp;1993 to September&nbsp;1995 he was the
Senior Vice President and Chief Financial Officer of IBM Corporation (&#147;<I>IBM</I>&#148;), and served as a member of IBM&#146;s Board of Directors from January&nbsp;1995 to August&nbsp;1995. Mr.&nbsp;York is also a member of the Board of
Directors of Tyco International&nbsp;Ltd. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Role of the Board; Corporate Governance Matters </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">It is the paramount duty of the Board to oversee the CEO and other senior management in the competent and ethical operation of the Company on a day-to-day
basis and to assure that the long-term interests of the shareholders are being served. To satisfy this duty, the directors take a proactive, focused approach to their position, and set standards to ensure that the Company is committed to business
success through maintenance of high standards of responsibility and ethics. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Members of the Board bring a wide range of experience,
knowledge and judgment to the Company. These varied skills mean that governance is far more than a &#147;check the box&#148; approach to standards or procedures. The </FONT>
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">4 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">governance structure in the Company is designed to be a working structure for principled actions, effective decision-making and appropriate monitoring of
both compliance and performance. The key practices and procedures of the Board are outlined in the Corporate Governance Guidelines available on the Company&#146;s website at www.apple.com/investor. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board met a total of seven (7) times during fiscal year 2007. The Board has determined that all Board members, excluding Steve Jobs, are independent
under the applicable NASDAQ rules. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Board Committees </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board has a standing Audit and Finance Committee (the &#147;<I>Audit Committee</I>&#148;), Compensation Committee (the &#147;<I>Compensation Committee</I>&#148;) and Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee
(the &#147;<I>Nominating Committee</I>&#148;). All committee members are independent under the listing standards of the NASDAQ Global Select Market. The members of the committees are identified in the table below. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Audit Committee is primarily responsible for overseeing the services performed by the
Company&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm and internal audit department, evaluating the Company&#146;s accounting policies and its system of internal controls and reviewing significant financial transactions. Members of the Audit
Committee are Messrs.&nbsp;Campbell and York and Dr.&nbsp;Levinson. The Audit Committee met a total of fourteen (14)&nbsp;times during fiscal year 2007. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee is primarily responsible for reviewing the compensation arrangements for the Company&#146;s executive officers, including the CEO, and for administering the Company&#146;s equity
compensation plans. Members of the Compensation Committee are Messrs.&nbsp;Campbell, Drexler and Gore. The Compensation Committee met a total of five (5)&nbsp;times during fiscal year 2007. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Nominating Committee assists the Board in identifying qualified individuals to become directors, determines the composition of the Board and its
committees, monitors the process to assess the Board&#146;s effectiveness and helps develop and implement the Company&#146;s corporate governance guidelines. The Nominating Committee also considers nominees proposed by shareholders. The Nominating
Committee is committed to actively seeking out highly qualified women and individuals from minority groups to include in the pool from which Board nominees are chosen. Members of the Nominating Committee are Messrs.&nbsp;Drexler and Gore and
Dr.&nbsp;Levinson. The Nominating Committee met a total of three (3)&nbsp;times during fiscal year 2007 and met subsequent to the end of the last fiscal year to recommend to the full Board each of the nominees for election to the Board, as presented
herein. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Audit, Compensation and Nominating Committees operate under written charters adopted by the Board. These charters are
available on the Company&#146;s website at www.apple.com/investor. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During fiscal year 2007, each member of the Board attended or
participated in seventy-five percent (75%)&nbsp;or more of the aggregate of (i)&nbsp;the total number of meetings of the Board held during the fiscal year or the portion thereof following such person&#146;s appointment to the Board and (ii)&nbsp;the
total number of meetings held by all </FONT>
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">5 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">committees on which such director served during the past fiscal year or the portion thereof following such person&#146;s appointment to one or more of those
committees. There are no family relationships among executive officers or directors of the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Audit Committee Financial Expert </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board has determined that all members of the Audit Committee, Messrs.&nbsp;Campbell and York and Dr.&nbsp;Levinson, qualify as &#147;audit committee
financial experts&#148; as defined by the SEC and also meet the additional criteria for independence of Audit Committee members set forth in Rule&nbsp;10A-3(b)(l) under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the&nbsp;&#147;<I>Exchange
Act</I>&#148;). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Code of Ethics </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
Company has a code of ethics that applies to all of the Company&#146;s employees, including its principal executive officer, principal financial officer and principal accounting officer, and the Board. A copy of this code, &#147;Ethics: The Way We
Do Business Worldwide,&#148; is available on the Company&#146;s website at www.apple.com/investor. The Company intends to disclose any changes in or waivers from its code of ethics by posting such information on its website or by filing a
Form&nbsp;8-K. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Compensation of Directors </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman"
SIZE="2">The form and amount of director compensation are determined by the Board after a review of recommendations made by the Nominating Committee. The current practice of the Board is to base a substantial portion of a director&#146;s annual
retainer on equity. Under the Company&#146;s 1997 Director Stock Option Plan (the &#147;<I>Director Plan</I>&#148;), members of the Board who are not also employees (&#147;<I>Non-Employee Directors</I>&#148;) are granted an option to acquire 30,000
shares of the Company&#146;s common stock upon their initial election to the Board (an &#147;<I>Initial Option</I>&#148;). Initial Options vest and become exercisable in equal installments on each of the first three anniversaries of the grant date.
On the fourth anniversary of a Non-Employee Director&#146;s initial election to the Board and on each subsequent anniversary thereafter, the director is granted an option to acquire 10,000 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock (an
&#147;<I>Annual Option</I>&#148;). Annual Options are fully vested and immediately exercisable on the date of grant. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Upon his initial
appointment to the Board on August&nbsp;29, 2006, Dr.&nbsp;Schmidt declined the annual retainer fee and the automatic stock option grant to purchase 30,000 shares to which new directors are entitled under the Director Plan. Instead, Dr.&nbsp;Schmidt
purchased 10,000 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock on the open market. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Non-Employee Directors also receive a $50,000 annual
retainer paid in quarterly installments. Beginning in the 2008 fiscal year, the chairperson of the Audit Committee is also entitled to an annual retainer of $25,000, in addition to the annual retainer paid to all Non-Employee Directors. In addition,
each Non-Employee Director is eligible to receive free of charge one of each new product introduced by the Company and is eligible to purchase additional equipment at a discount. Directors do not receive any additional consideration for serving as a
member or chairperson of any other committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Communications with the Board </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Any matter intended for the Board, or for any individual member or members of the Board, should be directed to the Company&#146;s Corporate Secretary at 1
Infinite Loop, Cupertino, California 95014, with a request to forward the same to the intended recipient. In general, all shareholder communication delivered to the Company&#146;s Corporate Secretary for forwarding to the Board or specified Board
members will be forwarded in accordance with the shareholder&#146;s instructions. However, the Company&#146;s Corporate Secretary reserves the right not to forward to Board members any abusive, threatening or otherwise inappropriate materials.
Information </FONT>
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">6 </FONT></P>

<FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">regarding the submission of comments or complaints relating to the Company&#146;s accounting, internal accounting controls or auditing matters can be found
on the Company&#146;s website at www.apple.com/investor. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company encourages all incumbent directors and nominees for election as
director to attend the Annual Meeting. Directors Steve Jobs, William Campbell, Arthur Levinson, Ph.D. and Eric Schmidt, Ph.D. attended the Annual Meeting in May 2007. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Compensation Committee Interlocks and Insider Participation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee members whose

SEC&#146;s rules requiring disclosure of certain relationships and related-party transactions. None of the Company&#146;s executive officers served as a director or a member of a compensation committee (or other committee serving an equivalent
function) of any other entity, the executive officers of which served as a director of the Company or member of the Compensation Committee during the 2007 fiscal year. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Timothy D. Cook,</B> Chief Operating Officer, joined the Company in March&nbsp;1998.
Mr.&nbsp;Cook also served in the position of Executive Vice President, Worldwide Sales and Operations from 2002 to 2005. In 2004, his responsibilities were expanded to include the Company&#146;s Macintosh hardware engineering. From 2000 to 2002,
Mr.&nbsp;Cook served in the role of Senior Vice President, Worldwide Operations, Sales, Service and Support. From 1998 to 2000, Mr.&nbsp;Cook served in the position of Senior Vice President, Worldwide Operations. Prior to joining the Company,
Mr.&nbsp;Cook held the position of Vice President, Corporate Materials for Compaq Computer Corporation (&#147;<I>Compaq</I>&#148;). Prior to his work at Compaq, Mr.&nbsp;Cook was the Chief Operating Officer of the Reseller Division at Intelligent
Electronics. Mr.&nbsp;Cook also spent 12&nbsp;years with IBM, most recently as Director of North American Fulfillment. Mr.&nbsp;Cook is also a member of the Board of Directors of Nike,&nbsp;Inc. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Daniel Cooperman,</B> Senior Vice President, General Counsel and Secretary, joined the Company in November&nbsp;2007. Prior to joining the Company, he
served as Senior Vice President, General Counsel and Secretary of Oracle Corporation since February&nbsp;1997. Prior to that, he had been associated with the law firm of McCutchen, Doyle, Brown&nbsp;&amp; Enersen (which is now Bingham McCutchen LLP)
since October&nbsp;1977, and had served as a partner since June&nbsp;1983. From September&nbsp;1995 until February&nbsp;1997, Mr.&nbsp;Cooperman was Chair of the </FONT>
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">7 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">law firm&#146;s Business and Transactions Group and from April&nbsp;1989 through September&nbsp;1995, he served as the Managing Partner of the law
firm&#146;s San&nbsp;Jose office. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Tony Fadell,</B> Senior Vice President, iPod Division, joined the Company in 2001. From 2004 to
April&nbsp;2006, Mr.&nbsp;Fadell was Vice President of iPod Engineering. From 2001 to 2004, Mr.&nbsp;Fadell was the Senior Director of the Company&#146;s iPod Engineering Team. Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Fadell was a co-founder, Chief
Technology Officer, and director of engineering of the Mobile Computing Group at Philips Electronics where he was responsible for all aspects of business and product development for a variety of products. Mr.&nbsp;Fadell later became Vice President
of Business Development for Philips U.S. Strategy&nbsp;&amp; Ventures, focusing on building the company&#146;s digital media strategy and investment portfolio. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Ronald B. Johnson,</B> Senior Vice President, Retail, joined the Company in January&nbsp;2000. Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Johnson spent 16&nbsp;years with Target Stores, most recently as Senior
Merchandising Executive. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Peter Oppenheimer,</B> Senior Vice President and Chief Financial Officer, joined the Company in
July&nbsp;1996. Mr.&nbsp;Oppenheimer also served the Company in the position of Vice President and Corporate Controller, and as Senior Director of Finance for the Americas. Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Oppenheimer was Chief Financial
Officer of one of the four business units for Automatic Data Processing,&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;<I>ADP</I>&#148;). Prior to joining ADP, Mr.&nbsp;Oppenheimer spent six years in the Information Technology Consulting Practice with Coopers and Lybrand.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Philip W. Schiller,</B> Senior Vice President, Worldwide Product Marketing, rejoined the Company in 1997. Prior to rejoining the
Company, Mr.&nbsp;Schiller was Vice President of Product Marketing at Macromedia,&nbsp;Inc. from December&nbsp;1995 to March&nbsp;1997 and Director of Product Marketing at FirePower Systems,&nbsp;Inc. from 1993 to December&nbsp;1995. Prior to that,
Mr.&nbsp;Schiller spent six years at the Company in various marketing positions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Bertrand Serlet,&nbsp;Ph.D.,</B> Senior Vice
President, Software Engineering, joined the Company in February&nbsp;1997 upon the Company&#146;s acquisition of NeXT and also served the Company in the position of Vice President of Platform Technology. At NeXT, Dr.&nbsp;Serlet held several
engineering and managerial positions, including Director of Web Engineering. Prior to NeXT, from 1985 to 1989, Dr.&nbsp;Serlet worked as a research engineer at Xerox PARC. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Sina Tamaddon,</B> Senior Vice President, Applications, joined the Company in September&nbsp;1997. Mr.&nbsp;Tamaddon has also served with the Company
in the position of Senior Vice President, Worldwide Service and Support, and Vice President and General Manager, Newton Group. Before joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Tamaddon held the position of Vice President, Europe with NeXT from
September&nbsp;1996 through March&nbsp;1997. From August&nbsp;1994 to August&nbsp;1996, Mr.&nbsp;Tamaddon held the position of Vice President, Professional Services with NeXT. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Security Ownership of Certain Beneficial Owners and Management </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table sets forth
certain information as of January 4, 2008 (the &#147;<I>Table Date</I>&#148;) with respect to the beneficial ownership of the Company&#146;s common stock by (i)&nbsp;each person the Company believes beneficially holds more than 5% of the outstanding
shares of the Company&#146;s common stock; (ii)&nbsp;each director; (iii)&nbsp;each named executive officer listed in the Summary Compensation Table under the section entitled &#147;<B>Executive Compensation</B>&#148;; and (iv)&nbsp;all directors
and executive officers as a group. On the Table Date, 878,711,290 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock were issued and outstanding. Unless otherwise indicated, all persons named as beneficial owners of the Company&#146;s common stock have sole
voting power and sole investment power with respect to the shares indicated as beneficially owned. In addition, unless otherwise indicated, all persons named below can be reached at Apple&nbsp;Inc., 1&nbsp;Infinite Loop, Cupertino, California 95014.

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(13)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Includes 1,529,233 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock that executive officers or directors have the right to acquire by exercise of stock options and excludes 3,148,000
unvested restricted stock units. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;*</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Represents less than 1% of the issued and outstanding shares of the Company&#146;s common stock on the Table Date. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Compliance with Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Exchange Act </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman"
SIZE="2">Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Exchange Act requires the Company&#146;s executive officers and directors, and persons who own more than ten percent of a registered class of the Company&#146;s equity securities, to file reports of securities
ownership and changes in such ownership with the SEC. Executive officers, directors and greater than ten percent shareholders also are required by rules promulgated by the SEC to furnish the Company with copies of all Section&nbsp;16(a) forms they
file. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Based solely upon a review of the copies of such forms furnished to the Company or written representations that no Forms&nbsp;5 were
required, the Company believes that all Section&nbsp;16(a) filing requirements were met during fiscal year 2007, except that (i)&nbsp;one Form&nbsp;4 was filed for William Campbell on October&nbsp;26, 2007 with respect to the purchase by
Mr.&nbsp;Campbell&#146;s independent money manager of 3,600, 2,600 and 2,900 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock, in February&nbsp;2006, September&nbsp;2006 and January&nbsp;2007, respectively, and the sale by Mr.&nbsp;Campbell&#146;s
independent money manager of 2,200, 1,400 and 2,600 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock in April&nbsp;2006, June&nbsp;2006 and July&nbsp;2007, respectively, and (ii)&nbsp;one Form&nbsp;4 was filed for Tony Fadell on November&nbsp;15, 2007 with
respect to the acquisition by Mr.&nbsp;Fadell&#146;s spouse of 40,000 restricted stock units in December&nbsp;2006 and 25,000 restricted stock units in October&nbsp;2007. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Review, Approval or Ratification of Transactions with Related Persons </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board has adopted a
written policy for approval of transactions between the Company and its directors, director nominees, executive officers, greater than five percent beneficial owners and their respective immediate family members, where the amount involved in the
transaction exceeds or is expected to exceed $120,000 in a single calendar year. A copy of this policy is available on the Company&#146;s website at www.apple.com/investor. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The policy provides that the Audit Committee reviews certain transactions subject to the policy and determines whether or not to approve or ratify those
transactions. In doing so, the Audit Committee takes into account, among other factors it deems appropriate: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the related person&#146;s interest in the transaction; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the approximate dollar value of the amount involved in the transaction; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the approximate dollar value of the amount of the related person&#146;s interest in the transaction without regard to the amount of any profit or loss;
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">whether the transaction was undertaken in the ordinary course of business of the Company; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">whether the transaction with the related person is proposed to be, or was, entered into on terms no less favorable to the Company than terms that could have been
reached with an unrelated third party; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the purpose of, and the potential benefits to the Company of, the transaction; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">any other information regarding the transaction or the related person in the context of the proposed transaction that would be material to investors in light of the
circumstances of the particular transaction. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, the Audit Committee has delegated authority to the Chair of
the Audit Committee to pre-approve or ratify certain transactions. A summary of any new transactions pre-approved or ratified by the Chair is provided to the full Audit Committee for its review in connection with its next scheduled Audit Committee
meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">10 </FONT></P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2001, the Company entered into a Reimbursement Agreement with the CEO, Mr.&nbsp;Jobs, for the reimbursement of expenses incurred by Mr.&nbsp;Jobs in the
operation of his private plane when used for the Company&#146;s business. The Company recognized a total of $776,000, $202,000, and $1,100,000 in expenses pursuant to the Reimbursement Agreement during 2007, 2006 and 2005, respectively.

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company enters into commercial dealings with The Walt Disney Company, Genentech and Google that it considers arms-length, including sales arrangements and, in
the case of Google, licensing agreements and similar arrangements and, in the case of The Walt Disney Company, iTunes Store content licensing agreements and similar agreements. The Company enters into these commercial dealings in the ordinary course
of its business. Mr.&nbsp;Jobs is a Director of The Walt Disney Company. Dr.&nbsp;Levinson is the Chief Executive Officer and a Director of Genentech. Dr.&nbsp;Schmidt is the Chief Executive Officer and a Director of Google, Dr. Levinson is a
Director of Google and Mr.&nbsp;Gore is a Senior Advisor to Google. The Company does not believe that any of Messrs.&nbsp;Jobs or Gore or Drs.&nbsp;Levinson or Schmidt has a material direct or indirect interest in any of such commercial dealings.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

participates in the Company&#146;s equity award and benefit programs. Her compensation is commensurate with that of her peers. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman"
SIZE="2">The Board has determined all Board members, excluding Mr.&nbsp;Jobs, are independent under the applicable NASDAQ rules. The Board has also determined the members of each committee of the Board are independent under the listing standards of
the NASDAQ Global Select Market. In making these determinations, the Board considered, among other things, the types and amounts of the commercial dealings between the Company and the companies and organizations with which the directors are
affiliated. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Report of the Compensation Committee </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>The following report of the Compensation Committee shall not be deemed to be &#147;soliciting material&#148; or to otherwise be considered
&#147;filed&#148; with the SEC, nor shall such information be incorporated by reference into any future filing under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended (the &#147;Securities Act&#148;) or the Exchange Act except to the extent that the Company
specifically incorporates it by reference into such filing. </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee consists of three Non-Employee Directors:
Messrs. Campbell, Drexler and Gore, each of whom the Board has determined is independent as defined by the NASDAQ Global Select Market listing standards. The Compensation Committee has certain duties and powers as described in its written charter
adopted by the Board. A copy of the charter can be found on the Company&#146;s website at www.apple.com/investor. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation
Committee has reviewed and discussed with management the disclosures contained in the section entitled &#147;<B>Compensation Discussion and Analysis</B>&#148; of this Proxy Statement. Based upon this review and discussion, the Compensation Committee
recommended to the Board that the section entitled &#147;<B>Compensation Discussion and Analysis</B>&#148; be included in this Proxy Statement for the Company&#146;s 2008 Annual Meeting of Shareholders. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Members of the Compensation Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
